<doc id="203962" wikidata="Q1151100" url="?curid=203962" title="Itô's lemma">
<text>In mathematics, Itô&#x27;s lemma or Itô&#x27;s formula is an identity used in Itô calculus to find the differential of a time-dependent function of a stochastic process. It serves as the stochastic calculus counterpart of the chain rule. It can be heuristically derived by forming the Taylor series expansion of the function up to its second derivatives and retaining terms up to first order in the time increment and second order in the Wiener process increment. The lemma is widely employed in mathematical finance, and its best known application is in the derivation of the Black–Scholes equation for option values.

This result was discovered by Japanese mathematician Kiyoshi Itô in 1951.

== Motivation ==
Suppose we are given the stochastic differential equation
formula_1
where is a Wiener process and the functions formula_2 are deterministic (not stochastic) functions of time. In general, it&#x27;s not possible to write a solution formula_3 directly in terms of formula_4 However, we can formally write an integral solution
formula_5

This expression lets us easily read off the mean and variance of formula_3 (which has no higher moments). First, notice that every formula_7 individually has mean 0, so the expected value of formula_3 is simply the integral of the drift function:
formula_9

Similarly, because the formula_10 terms have variance 1 and no correlation with one another, the variance of formula_3 is simply the integral of the variance of each infinitesimal step in the random walk:
formula_12

However, sometimes we are faced with a stochastic differential equation for a more complex process formula_13 in which the process appears on both sides of the differential equation. That is, say
formula_14
for some functions formula_15 and formula_16 In this case, we cannot immediately write a formal solution as we did for the simpler case above. Instead, we hope to write the process formula_17 as a function of a simpler process formula_3 taking the form above. That is, we want to identify three functions formula_19 and formula_20 such that formula_21 and formula_22 In practice, Ito&#x27;s lemma is used in order to find this transformation. Finally, once we have transformed the problem into the simpler type of problem, we can determine the mean and higher moments of the process.

