so we see that the product formula_120 is itself an Itô drift-diffusion process.

== Itô&#x27;s formula for functions with finite quadratic variation ==
Hans Föllmer provided a non-probabilistic proof of the Itô formula and showed that it holds for all functions with finite quadratic variation.

Let formula_121 be a real-valued function and formula_122 a right-continuous function with left limits and finite quadratic variation formula_123. Then
:formula_124

where the quadratic variation of $x$ is defined as a limit along a sequence of partitions formula_125 of formula_126 with step decreasing to zero:

formula_127

== Higher-order Itô formula==

